Cambess. Fl. Bras. Merid. 2 (19): 351. 1832.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C063261C7E347198362D4356D4FE340F" pageId="2" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName id="2CD6FFC1992C029B39F7DE8F0A3AA6C0" authorityName="de Oliveira Bünger &amp; Mazine &amp; Lucas &amp; Stehmann" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eugenia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eugenia subsp. sect." order="Myrtales" pageId="2" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="section" section="Speciosae" species="speciosa" subSpecies="sect.">Eugenia sect. Speciosae</taxonomicName>
contains six species with three occurring in the Atlantic Forest of Brazil, and one distributed in northern South America, in the Amazon. The Atlantic Forest-Amazon disjunction distribution represents a classic biogeographic pattern of the Southern Hemisphere (
<bibRefCitation id="D549F144884CCE4B63A13FCA8BFEAECF" author="McVaugh, R" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" pagination="354 - 418" publicationUrl="10.2307/1217393" refId="B11" refString="McVaugh, R, 1968. The genera of American Myrtaceae - an interim report. Taxon 17: 354 - 418, DOI: 10.2307/1217393" title="The genera of American Myrtaceae - an interim report." url="10.2307/1217393" volume="17" year="1968">McVaugh 1968</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
